Data Wrangling and Visualization of Snow Hares

Benson Truong

# Attach library
library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)
library(kableExtra)
library(naniar)
library(ggfortify)
library(lubridate)

Introduction

Snowshoe hares are critical keystone species in northern boreal forests, so it is important to monitor thier population size. Snowshoe data was collected at the Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest and provided by the Environmental Data Initiative. In this study, the counts of snowshoe population and a table statistic, both within a 15 year span, are presented. Note, this data was filtered and wrangled based on missing values and unidentified values.

Figure 1. Photo of a Snowshoe Hare. Credit: Cottage Life

# Read in snowshoe data
snowshoe <- read_csv("showshoe_lter.csv")

# Tidy data
snowshoe_tidy <- snowshoe %>% 
  mutate(sex = str_to_lower(sex)) %>%
  mutate(new_date = mdy(date)) %>% 
  mutate(year = year(new_date))

# Filtered data
snowshoe_filter <- snowshoe_tidy %>% 
  filter(sex == c("m", "f")) %>% 
  drop_na(weight, hindft)

# Data for plot
graph_data <- snowshoe_filter %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarize(
    counts = n()
  )
# Plot
ggplot(data = graph_data) +
  geom_col(aes(x = year, y = counts),
           fill = "white",
           color = "black") +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Snowshoe Counts", title = "Counts of Snowshoe from Years 1998 - 2012") +
  theme_dark() +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 125), expand = c(0,0)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1998:2012, labels = c("'98","'99","'00","'01","'02","'03","'04","'05","'06", "'07","'08","'09","'10","'11", "'12"), expand = c(.01,.01))

Figure 2. The number of snowshoes observed from years 1998-2012.

The fluctuations of the snowshoe populations is illustrated above and can be explained by predator-prey cycles. The smallest snowshoe hare population was observed in 1998 while the largest was observed in year 2009.

Table 1. Summary statistics of snowshoe weights and hind feet lengths based on sex from years 1998-2012.

# Summary table
snowshoe_table <- snowshoe_filter%>% 
  group_by(sex) %>% 
  summarize(
    counts = n(),
    avg_weight = mean(weight),
    avg_length = mean(hindft)
  ) %>% 
  adorn_rounding(digits = 1)

snowshoe_table$sex <- gsub("f", "FEMALE", snowshoe_table$sex)
snowshoe_table$sex <- gsub("m", "MALE", snowshoe_table$sex)

# kableExtra
kable(snowshoe_table, col.names = c("Sex", "Counts", "Average Weight (g)", "Average Length (mm)"), align = "c") %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE,
                bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover"))
Sex Counts Average Weight (g) Average Length (mm)
FEMALE 419 1326.7 130.2
MALE 313 1315.5 133.3

The average weight and hind feet length of the female and male snowshoe hares are relatively similar. There are also 100+ more counts of females than males in this dataset.
